    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "Load metric.csv, trace.csv, log.csv, and error_logs.csv. For each file, compute and return a compact summary containing: total number of rows; minimum timestamp and maximum timestamp; number of unique cmdb_id; list of unique cmdb_id (sorted) limited to first 50 entries; number of unique KPI/trace/log names (for metric use kpi_name, for trace use trace_name, for log use log_name, for error_logs show count of distinct messages); list of unique KPI/trace/log names with their occurrence counts, limited to top 50 by count. Additionally for metric.csv only: provide the top 20 (cmdb_id, kpi_name) pairs by row count with their counts. Keep outputs as plain text/tabular and limit rows as requested."
}

{
    "analysis": "We computed global P95/P5 per (cmdb_id,kpi_name) and scanned the incident window. The top anomaly hits were dominated by many adservice KPIs that are constant across the full series (30 points) so their global_p95 == global_p5 == observed value, causing every point to be flagged as both >=P95 and <=P5. These are likely instrumentation/constant series and not informative for root-cause. We need to find metric series that show meaningful deviations (non-constant) during the incident window: either spikes above global_p95 by a significant margin, or drops below global_p5 (especially for traffic/business KPIs). From those, we can shortlist candidate components and timestamps for trace/log analysis.",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "On metric.csv only, recompute per (cmdb_id,kpi_name) using the full series: total_points, global_p95, global_p5. Then filter rows to the incident window 2022-03-20 21:00:00 to 2022-03-20 21:30:00 (UTC+8) and for each pair compute: points_in_window, anomaly_count_above_p95, anomaly_count_below_p5, earliest_anomaly_ts_in_window, max_value_in_window, min_value_in_window, std_in_window, and a flag constant_series (True if max_value_in_window == min_value_in_window). Define deviation_score = max( max_value_in_window - global_p95 (if positive), global_p5 - min_value_in_window (if positive) ). Exclude constant_series True. Return the top 20 (cmdb_id,kpi_name) pairs sorted by deviation_score descending. For each returned row include: cmdb_id, kpi_name, total_points, global_p95, global_p5, points_in_window, anomaly_count_above_p95, anomaly_count_below_p5, earliest_anomaly_ts_in_window, max_value_in_window, min_value_in_window, std_in_window, deviation_score. Also return the distinct list of cmdb_id values found among these top 20 (compact). Limit output to 20 rows."
}

{
    "analysis": "We already performed metric-based anomaly scanning: global thresholds (P95/P5) were computed on full series and the incident window was scanned. Results show candidate components concentrated on adservice/adservice2 (many JVM CPU/threading/alloc metrics) and several node/container memory and filesystem metrics (node-3/node-4/node-6, frontend2-0, adservice2-0, currencyservice2-0). Many series are non-constant but only show a few points crossing thresholds (often 2 above / 2 below) with earliest anomaly timestamps at the start of the window (2022-03-20 21:00:00+08). error_logs.csv earlier indicated many repeated warning messages from frontend-0/1/2, which may be symptoms. To decide the root cause component (service/pod/node) we must now use traces to find which faulty component is the most downstream in call chains and whether any service-level traces show elevated error_rate or latency correlated with the metric anomalies. Traces will help distinguish between multiple candidate container/service faults. Next step: perform an aggregate, threshold-based scan on trace.csv limited to the candidate cmdb_id list from metrics to identify trace series with meaningful anomalies inside the incident window and earliest anomaly times.",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "On trace.csv only: restrict analysis to the candidate cmdb_id set [adservice, adservice2, adservice2-0, currencyservice2-0, frontend2-0, node-3, node-4, node-6]. For each unique (cmdb_id, trace_name) compute using the full available series (do NOT filter by time yet): total_points, global_p95, global_p5. Then filter to the incident window 2022-03-20 21:00:00 to 2022-03-20 21:30:00 (UTC+8) and compute: points_in_window, anomaly_count_above_p95 (value >= global_p95), anomaly_count_below_p5 (value <= global_p5), earliest_anomaly_ts_in_window (smallest timestamp in window where either condition holds), avg_value_in_window, max_value_in_window, min_value_in_window. Return a compact table limited to top 20 rows sorted by (anomaly_count_above_p95 + anomaly_count_below_p5) descending; for ties sort by earliest_anomaly_ts_in_window ascending. Include these columns: cmdb_id, trace_name, total_points, global_p95, global_p5, points_in_window, anomaly_count_above_p95, anomaly_count_below_p5, earliest_anomaly_ts_in_window, avg_value_in_window, max_value_in_window, min_value_in_window. Also return a short separate list of trace_name types among results that indicate error_rate or duration or row_count (if present). Limit outputs to top 20 rows."
}

{
    "analysis": "We inspected metrics and traces for the incident window. Metric analysis found candidate components concentrated on adservice/adservice2 (JVM CPU/threading/alloc metrics) and on several container memory cache metrics (adservice2-0, frontend2-0) and node filesystem/disk metrics (node-3/node-4/node-6). Many metric anomalies have earliest timestamps at the start of the window (2022-03-20 21:00:00+08) but only a few points breach thresholds (commonly 2 above and 2 below). Trace analysis (restricted to metric candidates) showed most error_rate traces are constant-zero (artefacts), while non-constant traces of interest include frontend2-0.trace.to_checkoutservice2-0.row_count (anomalous counts, earliest 21:00:00+08) and currencyservice2-0.trace.from_checkoutservice2-0.row_count (earliest 21:02:00+08). Duration metrics on frontend2-0 and adservice2-0 show small deviations with earliest anomalies around 21:01–21:03+08. Separately, error_logs.csv previously returned 1,592 repeated warning messages from frontend-0/1/2, suggesting frontend pods emitted warnings across the window. To localize the root cause further we must analyze logs: quantify which frontend pods logged warnings/errors during the window, earliest log times, and whether log.error_count in log.csv spikes correlate with metric/trace anomalies (especially frontend2-0). This will help determine whether the frontend pods are symptomatic or causal, and whether the fault originated at a container (frontend2-0/adservice2-0) or node level.",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "Analyze log.csv and error_logs.csv for the incident window 2022-03-20 21:00:00 to 2022-03-20 21:30:00 (UTC+8):\n1) From error_logs.csv: aggregate by cmdb_id and return for each cmdb_id (sorted by count desc, limit 20): total_count, earliest_timestamp_in_window, latest_timestamp_in_window, sample_message_text (first 200 characters). Also return the overall earliest error_logs timestamp across all cmdb_ids and the total number of error_logs in the window.\n2) From log.csv: for each cmdb_id compute (limit output to top 20 cmdb_ids by sum of log.error_count in the window): total_rows_for_cmdb (in file), points_in_window (rows within the incident window), sum_log_error_count_in_window (sum of value where log_name == 'log.error_count'), max_log_error_count_in_window, earliest_timestamp_in_window_where_log.error_count>0 (if any, else null). Also include the list of unique log_name values seen for those top cmdb_ids. Return compact table(s) only (no raw full series)."
}

